    <div class="sheet-container">
        <header class="text-center pb-4 border-b-2 border-gray-400">
            <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-800">Differentiation Rule Flowchart</h1>
            <h2 class="text-lg text-gray-600">How to Choose the Right Rule</h2>
        </header>

        <main class="mt-8">
            <div class="flowchart space-y-2">
                <!-- Start -->
                <div class="flow-step font-bold bg-green-100 border-green-200">Start with a function $$y = f(x)$$</div>
                <div class="flow-connector">▼</div>
                
                <!-- Step 1 -->
                <div class="flow-step">Is it a single "basic" function? <br><small class="text-gray-500">(e.g., $$x^n, e^x, \sin x$$)</small></div>
                <div class="flex">
                    <div class="w-1/2 p-2 text-center"><span class="font-bold text-green-700">YES</span><div class="flow-result bg-green-100 border-green-200 text-green-800">Use Basic Derivative Rules</div></div>
                    <div class="w-1/2 p-2 text-center"><span class="font-bold text-red-700">NO</span><div class="flow-connector">▼</div></div>
                </div>

                <!-- Step 2 -->
                <div class="flow-step">Is it a sum or difference? <br><small class="text-gray-500">$$f(x) \pm g(x)$$</small></div>
                 <div class="flex">
                    <div class="w-1/2 p-2 text-center"><span class="font-bold text-green-700">YES</span><div class="flow-result bg-green-100 border-green-200 text-green-800">Use Sum/Difference Rule</div></div>
                    <div class="w-1/2 p-2 text-center"><span class="font-bold text-red-700">NO</span><div class="flow-connector">▼</div></div>
                </div>

                <!-- Step 3 -->
                <div class="flow-step">Is it a product of two functions? <br><small class="text-gray-500">$$f(x) \cdot g(x)$$</small></div>
                <div class="flex">
                    <div class="w-1/2 p-2 text-center"><span class="font-bold text-green-700">YES</span><div class="flow-result bg-green-100 border-green-200 text-green-800">Use Product Rule</div></div>
                    <div class="w-1/2 p-2 text-center"><span class="font-bold text-red-700">NO</span><div class="flow-connector">▼</div></div>
                </div>

                <!-- Step 4 -->
                <div class="flow-step">Is it a quotient of two functions? <br><small class="text-gray-500">$$f(x) / g(x)$$</small></div>
                <div class="flex">
                    <div class="w-1/2 p-2 text-center"><span class="font-bold text-green-700">YES</span><div class="flow-result bg-green-100 border-green-200 text-green-800">Use Quotient Rule</div></div>
                    <div class="w-1/2 p-2 text-center"><span class="font-bold text-red-700">NO</span><div class="flow-connector">▼</div></div>
                </div>
                
                <!-- Step 5 -->
                 <div class="flow-step">Is it a function inside another function? <br><small class="text-gray-500">$$f(g(x))$$</small></div>
                <div class="flex">
                    <div class="w-1/2 p-2 text-center"><span class="font-bold text-green-700">YES</span><div class="flow-result bg-green-100 border-green-200 text-green-800">Use Chain Rule</div></div>
                     <div class="w-1/2 p-2 text-center"><span class="font-bold text-red-700">NO</span><div class="flow-connector">▼</div></div>
                </div>

                <!-- End -->
                 <div class="flow-step">Check for special cases <br><small class="text-gray-500">(logarithmic, inverse trig, etc.)</small></div>
            </div>

            <div class="mt-12 pt-8 border-t-2 border-gray-300 example-section">
                <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-6 text-center">Usage Examples</h3>
                <div class="space-y-6 text-lg">
                    <p><strong>1. Example: $$y = x^4 + e^x$$</strong><br><span class="ml-4">→ This is a sum. ✅ Use the <strong>Sum Rule</strong>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong>2. Example: $$y = (2x)(\sin x)$$</strong><br><span class="ml-4">→ This is a product. ✅ Use the <strong>Product Rule</strong>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong>3. Example: $$y = \frac{x}{e^x}$$</strong><br><span class="ml-4">→ This is a quotient. ✅ Use the <strong>Quotient Rule</strong>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong>4. Example: $$y = e^{3x^2}$$</strong><br><span class="ml-4">→ This is a function ($$3x^2$$) inside another ($$e^u$$). ✅ Use the <strong>Chain Rule</strong>.</span></p>
                    <p><strong>5. Example: $$y = \ln(x^2+1)$$</strong><br><span class="ml-4">→ This is a function ($$x^2+1$$) inside a special case ($$\ln u$$). ✅ Use the <strong>Chain Rule</strong> and the rule for natural logs.</span></p>
                </div>
            </div>
